title: For Sale:  Spanish-made "Ruby" gun – Almost an Antique – 7.65/.32 Auto
postcontent: My father returned from WW II with this sweet, old pistol. He probably picked it up from someone in the French military. After WW I, France asked manufacturers in Spain to create a carry gun for its military. Dozens of Spanish factories built guns of this design.  For the complete story on these guns, see: http://www.reenactor.net/units/151ri/weps/ruby_pistol.htm  This gun was made by La Industria Orbea, Eibar, Spain. That's what the fading etching on the side of the slide indicates (above the "CAL 7.65" marking). Beneath the right end of the slide is a stamped "IO" inside an oval. That indicates the gun was made by Industrie Orbea. The same logo appears on the bottom of the clip, which shows it is original.  At the base of the handle are stamped two stars, "**." This indicates the gun was used by the French military.  At the back of the slide is an engraved "TC" that looks like the logo on the caps of the Minnesota Twins. I have diminished its appearance with a dose from a Gun Blue Pen from Birchwood Casey.  The gun comes with an authentic military type holster with the flap over the gun and a pocket for the clip. I am also including the hard plastic case in which it is set for the photo. For a local sale, I will include about 1 1/2 boxes of .32 Auto ammo.  I also have for sale a brown leather holster my father usually kept the gun in. It's vintage, from Brauer Bros. in St. Louis. Those go for about $40 on eBay.  I just took the one photo because I wanted to get this uploaded as soon as possible. I will take more if someone requests them.  Asking price is for local pick up. If I have to ship it to your FFL holder, the cost should be an additional around $45. That's what it cost when I shipped a pistol last month.

title: For Sale:  6mm Flobert
postcontent:
Marke Eiche Model 101 rifle: Caliber 6mm Flobert --- Rifled bore for BB or CB. $75.
A European caliber circa 1888, .22cal CB (conical ball) often called parlor or Garden Rifle, this one is dated on buttstock 1 -12-38. Meaning January 1938. Making this German Training rifle 78 years old tomorrow (today). CCI makes 6mm Flobert or their label 22CB. This is a simple cap and ball round using only the primer slurry of a 22 cartridge as propellant. It should not be shot with 22short/LR. Check the FPS per round vs a 6mm FLobert.
Research link - http://www.thecuckoofarm.com/cuckoo/firearm/rifle/flob/flob.php This is an excellent research page and about the only on in English. Lots of German and Russian/Baltic reference that don’t translate well.
WIKI page is titled .22CB. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/.22_CB

title: For Sale:  Remington MLE 190715 RAG 1907-15 8mm Lebel
postcontent:
Call/Text REDACTED
Make this historical piece apart of your collection!Excellent mechanical condition.
Remington MLE 190715 RAG 1907-15 8mm Lebel French Berthier Sporter Remington Factory Berthier Bolt Action Sporting Rifle. Curio/relic. Cal. 8mm Lebel. Manuf. Remington Arms 1918. This is one of the rarely seen Remington Factory Berthier sporting conversions. Because the demand for rifles could not be met by their own industry, France contracted with Remington Arms to manufacture the Model 07/15. For unknown reasons the Berthier’s magazine capacity was three rounds while German rifles held five rounds, and British 10 rounds. When World War I began the French quickly realized the problems with the Berthier. The Model 1907 was modified by adding a metal extension to the bottom of the rifle so a five round clip could be loaded. Thus the rifle Model 07/15. It became the primary rifle of the French army during World War I. Many of these rifles were re-imported after the end of World War I and sold on the surplus market. Remington was stuck with these guns after WWI when the French refused to pay for them. They then decided to cut their losses by converting a number of them to sporting rifles. The walnut stock has been cut down for sport use and is in good condition with handling marks and dings. The blueing is about 25% on the metal surfaces with minor pitting from old rust and light corrosion from sweat especially on the trigger guard. The bore is good with definitive rifling with no visible pitting. Remington never serialized these and there are no numbers on it anywhere. Comes with the hard to find three round enbloc. The 8mm Lebel is a very powerful round and is readily available at an affordable price from PRIVI and is adequate for all North American big game. This rifle has a unique sight combination of a rear and front peep sight that is very easy to use. Overall the rifle is in good condition for a nearly 100 year old sporterized war relic. We have shot this rifle and it certainly gets the attention at the range.

title: For Sale:  Remington MLE 190715 RAG 1907-15 8mm Lebel
postcontent: Call/Text919-404-9336Make this historical piece apart of your collection!Excellent mechanical condition.Remington MLE 190715 RAG 1907-15 8mm Lebel French Berthier Sporter Remington Factory Berthier Bolt Action Sporting Rifle. Curio/relic. Cal. 8mm Lebel. Manuf. Remington Arms 1918. This is one of the rarely seen Remington Factory Berthier sporting conversions. Because the demand for rifles could not be met by their own industry, France contracted with Remington Arms to manufacture the Model 07/15. For unknown reasons the Berthier’s magazine capacity was three rounds while German rifles held five rounds, and British 10 rounds. When World War I began the French quickly realized the problems with the Berthier. The Model 1907 was modified by adding a metal extension to the bottom of the rifle so a five round clip could be loaded. Thus the rifle Model 07/15. It became the primary rifle of the French army during World War I. Many of these rifles were re-imported after the end of World War I and sold on the surplus market. Remington was stuck with these guns after WWI when the French refused to pay for them. They then decided to cut their losses by converting a number of them to sporting rifles. The walnut stock has been cut down for sport use and is in good condition with handling marks and dings. The blueing is about 25% on the metal surfaces with minor pitting from old rust and light corrosion from sweat especially on the trigger guard. The bore is good with definitive rifling with no visible pitting. Remington never serialized these and there are no numbers on it anywhere. The 8mm Lebel is a very powerful round and is readily available at an affordable price from PRIVI and is adequate for all North American big game. This rifle has a unique sight combination of a rear and front peep sight that is very easy to use. Overall the rifle is in good condition for a nearly 100 year old sporterized war relic. We have shot this rifle and it certainly gets the attention at the range.
